Below is a **complete, self‑contained binding** for the (hypothetical) C++ library **libpcapng**.  
It shows

* the public OCaml interface (`pcapng.mli`);
* the C‑/C++ stub file (`pcapng_stubs.c`) that can be compiled with a C++ compiler;
* a tiny example of how an OCaml program would use the binding.

The design keeps the C++ objects opaque on the OCaml side (custom blocks) and
offers two ways of walking the collection:

1. **Explicit pull** – `next` returns the next frame, or `None` when the iterator
   is exhausted.
2. **Push style** – `iter` takes an OCaml closure and calls it for every frame,
   which is the most convenient for OCaml users.

Both styles are implemented on top of the same low‑level iterator.

---

## 1. OCaml public interface (`pcapng.mli`)

```ocaml
(*--------------------------------------------------------------------
   pcapng.mli – public interface for the libpcapng binding
  --------------------------------------------------------------------*)

(** {1 Types} *)

type parser   (** opaque handle to a libpcapng parser/iterator *)
type frame    (** opaque handle to a single captured frame *)

(** {1 Opening / closing} *)

val open_file : string -> parser
(** Open a pcapng file and return a parser.  Raises [Failure] if the file
    cannot be opened or is not a valid pcapng file. *)

val close : parser -> unit
(** Release all resources associated with the parser.  After calling [close]
    the parser must not be used any more. *)

(** {1 Pull style access} *)

val next : parser -> frame option
(** Return the next frame, or [None] when the iterator has reached the end.
    The returned [frame] is owned by the parser and must not be freed by the
    caller. *)

(** {1 Push style access – the “iterate” API} *)

val iter : parser -> (frame -> unit) -> unit
(** Walk the whole collection, calling the supplied closure for each frame.
    The closure is allowed to raise an exception; iteration stops and the
    exception propagates to the caller. *)

(** {1 Inspecting a frame} *)

val data      : frame -> bytes
(** Raw packet payload (as a fresh copy of the underlying data). *)

val length    : frame -> int
(** Length of the payload in bytes. *)

val timestamp : frame -> float
(** Timestamp of the frame, expressed as seconds since the Unix epoch. *)

(** {1 Convenience helpers} *)

val with_file : string -> (parser -> 'a) -> 'a
(** Open a file, run the supplied function, then automatically close the
    parser (even if the function raises).  Equivalent to:

    {[
      let p = open_file fname in
      Fun.protect ~finally:(fun () -> close p) (fun () -> f p)
    ]}
*)
```

